  "prompt": "What is the legal status of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal crime in the United States, as well as in many countries around the world. It's illegal under various statutes, primarily:\n\n*   **18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments:** This section prohibits a wide range of activities intended to conceal or disguise the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of illegally obtained money.\n*   **18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity:** This section prohibits knowingly engaging in a monetary transaction (over \\$10,000) with property derived from specified unlawful activity (SUA).\n\n**Key Elements of Money Laundering:**\n\n*   **Illegal Proceeds:** The money or property involved must be derived from an illegal source (a \"specified unlawful activity,\" or SUA).\n*   **Knowledge:** The person involved must know that the property is derived from illegal activity.\n*   **Intent:** In many cases, the prosecution must prove that the person acted with the intent to conceal the source of the funds, promote further criminal activity, or avoid reporting requirements.\n\n**Penalties:**\n\nPenalties for money laundering are severe and can include:\n\n*   **Significant Fines:** Millions of dollars per violation.\n*   **Lengthy Prison Sentences:** Up to 20 years per violation.\n*   **Asset Forfeiture:** The government can seize assets involved in or derived from the money laundering scheme.\n*   **Civil Penalties:** In addition to criminal penalties, civil penalties may also be imposed.\n\n**International Aspects:**\n\nMoney laundering is also addressed by international treaties and conventions, such as the United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime and the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations. These aim to coordinate international efforts to combat money laundering and terrorist financing.",
